  <h3>The USP Degradation Model</h3>
  <p>The three-tier degradation hierarchy is the project's conceptual centerpiece and is correctly implemented at the type level. Bitcoin and Sui correctly avoid nullifiers (L1 structural). Aptos correctly relies on Move's linear type system (L2). Ethereum correctly uses a nullifier contract (L3). This honest modeling of differing security guarantees is a notable strength — most competing designs pretend all chains are equivalent.</p>

  <h3>Critical Architectural Issues</h3>

  <table class="finding-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Component</th>
        <th>Issue</th>
        <th>Severity</th>
        <th>Impact</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Right::verify()</td>
        <td>Does not verify the ownership proof cryptographically — only checks proof bytes are non-empty. An attacker can supply a 1-byte proof and pass verification.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span></td>
        <td>Security guarantee null</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>ConsignmentValidator</td>
        <td>Steps 2 (commitment chain) and 4 (state transitions) unconditionally return <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--amber)">true</code>. "Placeholder" comments confirm intent but not execution.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span></td>
        <td>CSV engine non-functional</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>MPT Proof Verification</td>
        <td><code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">verify_storage_proof()</code> and <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">verify_receipt_proof()</code> check only that inputs are non-empty, not that the trie path is valid.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span></td>
        <td>Ethereum proof forgeable</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Bitcoin publish()</td>
        <td>Transaction builder (<code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">tx_builder.rs</code>) is complete but NOT wired into the main publish() path. Returns placeholder txid in real mode.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-high">High</span></td>
        <td>Can't anchor on Bitcoin</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Aptos submit_transaction()</td>
        <td>Returns hardcoded <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--amber)">b"aptos-submit"</code> bytes as a transaction hash — never hits the network.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-high">High</span></td>
        <td>Can't publish on Aptos</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Cross-chain transfer</td>
        <td>CLI cross-chain flow uses hardcoded placeholder block heights (<code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">299239u64</code>) and Merkle branches (<code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">[0xCD;32]</code>). Not real.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-high">High</span></td>
        <td>Cross-chain claims false</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Tagged hashing</td>
        <td>BIP-340 tagged hash infrastructure exists but raw <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">Sha256::new()</code> is used in 12+ places: right.rs ID/nullifier, genesis.rs, transition.rs, all four chain proof modules.</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-medium">Medium</span></td>
        <td>Domain separation absent</td>
      </tr>
