<!-- SECTION 4: SECURITY -->
<section>
  <div class="section-tag">04 · Security Findings</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Security Vulnerabilities & Risks</h2>

  <ul class="risk-list">
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-01</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>Ownership proof not cryptographically verified</strong>
        <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">Right::verify()</code> checks <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">!self.owner.proof.is_empty()</code> but does not verify the signature against the Right's commitment or a known public key. Any non-empty byte slice passes. This nullifies the primary ownership security invariant.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-02</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>L1/L2 Rights can be "consumed" without chain confirmation</strong>
        For Bitcoin and Sui, <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">Right::consume(None)</code> returns <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">None</code> and sets no nullifier. The Right still passes <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">verify()</code>. This is by design but means that without checking the chain seal registry, a client cannot detect that a Right has been spent.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-high">High</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-03</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>Ethereum proof forgery: MPT verification is stub</strong>
        <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">verify_receipt_proof()</code> only checks that <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">!proof_nodes.is_empty()</code>. An adversary can submit a single fabricated node and pass inclusion verification. The <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">alloy-trie</code> dependency exists but its actual trie reconstruction is not called.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-04</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>RightId can be spoofed during deserialization</strong>
        <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">from_canonical_bytes()</code> reads the RightId directly from bytes without recomputing it from <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">H(commitment || salt)</code> (salt is not stored). An attacker crafting a serialized Right can set any RightId without invalidating the structure.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-high">High</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-05</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>Nullifier scope is an unresolved open design question</strong>
        The README explicitly flags "Nullifier scope: undecided." If a nullifier is computed as <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">H(right_id || secret)</code> but <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">right_id</code> is predictable (derived from commitment + public salt), the nullifier can be front-run or pre-computed.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-high">High</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-06</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>Raw SHA-256 used without domain separation in critical paths</strong>
        The Right ID is computed as <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">Sha256(commitment || salt)</code> without a domain tag. The nullifier as <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">Sha256(right_id || secret)</code>. The tagged hash infrastructure exists in <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">tagged_hash.rs</code> but is not used in these critical constructions, creating potential cross-context collision vulnerabilities.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-medium">Medium</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-07</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>new_unchecked() bypasses all validation</strong>
        Both <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">SealRef::new_unchecked()</code> and <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">AnchorRef::new_unchecked()</code> are public. The comment "for internal use only" is not enforced. Any caller can create oversized seal/anchor references and bypass the 1KB/4KB limits intended to prevent DoS.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-medium">Medium</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-08</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>CSVMint.sol verifies nothing on-chain</strong>
        The <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">mintRight()</code> function accepts the caller's word that a cross-chain lock occurred. No proof is verified on-chain. The comment acknowledges this ("For now, we trust the client-side verification pipeline") but it means the contract provides no security beyond a mapping of minted IDs.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-critical">Critical</span>
    </li>
    <li class="risk-item">
      <span class="risk-num">R-09</span>
      <div class="risk-text">
        <strong>No fuzz testing, property testing, or external audit</strong>
        The serialization/deserialization code (<code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">from_canonical_bytes</code>, RLP decoder, BCS builder) handles untrusted bytes with many manual bounds checks. This is exactly the code profile that produces CVEs under fuzzing. No fuzzing infrastructure exists.
      </div>
      <span class="badge badge-high">High</span>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 5: BLUEPRINT -->
<section>
  <div class="section-tag">05 · Architectural Blueprint</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Refined Architecture for Production</h2>

  <p>The current architecture requires targeted evolution in three dimensions: cryptographic completeness, validation pipeline closure, and cross-chain proof integrity. The following blueprint preserves all existing design decisions while specifying precisely what must change.</p>

  <h3>Core Abstractions — Required Refinements</h3>

  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><span class="cm">// CURRENT (insecure): ownership proof not verified</span>
<span class="kw">pub fn</span> <span class="ty">verify</span>(&self) -> Result&lt;(), RightError&gt; {
    <span class="kw">if</span> self.owner.proof.is_empty() {   <span class="cm">// only checks non-empty!</span>
        <span class="kw">return</span> Err(RightError::MissingOwnershipProof);
    }
    ...
}

<span class="cm">// REQUIRED: cryptographic verification</span>
<span class="kw">pub fn</span> <span class="ty">verify</span>(&self, chain_ctx: &<span class="ty">ChainVerificationContext</span>) -> Result&lt;(), RightError&gt; {
    <span class="cm">// 1. Verify signature over commitment using chain-specific scheme</span>
    chain_ctx.verify_ownership(&self.owner, &self.commitment)?;
    <span class="cm">// 2. Recompute and verify RightId  </span>
    <span class="cm">// 3. Check chain registry for seal consumption</span>
    ...
}</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>New Required Interface: ProofVerificationContext</h3>
  <p>The <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:12px">AnchorLayer</code> trait is well-designed but incomplete for cross-chain verification. A companion trait is needed that any client can implement to verify proofs originating from any chain without owning a connection to that chain.</p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><span class="cm">/// New trait: verify proofs from any chain without a live connection</span>
<span class="kw">pub trait</span> <span class="ty">ProofVerifier</span>: Send + Sync {
    <span class="cm">/// Verify that a transaction was included in a block at the stated height.</span>
    <span class="cm">/// Must perform cryptographic verification, not presence check.</span>
    <span class="kw">fn</span> verify_inclusion(
        &self,
        proof: &<span class="ty">InclusionProof</span>,
        expected_commitment: <span class="ty">Hash</span>,
    ) -> Result&lt;<span class="ty">VerifiedAnchor</span>, <span class="ty">ProofError</span>&gt;;

    <span class="cm">/// Verify that a block/checkpoint is final (irreversible).</span>
    <span class="kw">fn</span> verify_finality(
        &self,
        proof: &<span class="ty">FinalityProof</span>,
        current_tip: <span class="ty">BlockRef</span>,
    ) -> Result&lt;<span class="ty">FinalityStatus</span>, <span class="ty">ProofError</span>&gt;;

    <span class="cm">/// Chain this verifier was built for.</span>
    <span class="kw">fn</span> chain_id(&self) -> <span class="ty">ChainId</span>;
}

<span class="cm">/// Stateless verifiers (no RPC) for each chain</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="ty">BitcoinMerkleVerifier</span>;     <span class="cm">// uses SPV: proof + headers only</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="ty">EthereumMPTVerifier</span>;        <span class="cm">// reconstructs trie, verifies root</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="ty">SuiCheckpointVerifier</span>;      <span class="cm">// verifies validator cert signatures</span>
<span class="kw">pub struct</span> <span class="ty">AptosLedgerVerifier</span>;        <span class="cm">// verifies HotStuff quorum cert</span></pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Validation Pipeline — Closure Requirements</h3>

  <table class="matrix">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Pipeline Step</th>
        <th>Current State</th>
        <th>Required State</th>
        <th>Implementation Path</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>1. Structural validation</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Real</span></td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Keep as-is</span></td>
        <td>No action needed</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>2. Commitment chain walk</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-stub">Always passes</span></td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Cryptographic chain walk</span></td>
        <td>Wire existing <code style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px">verify_ordered_commitment_chain()</code> into ConsignmentValidator step 2</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>3. Seal consumption check</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Real (registry)</span></td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Keep + add chain-proof check</span></td>
        <td>Add call to chain-specific ProofVerifier before accepting</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>4. State transition validation</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-stub">Always passes</span></td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">VM-executed</span></td>
        <td>Route through PassthroughVM → actual VM implementation; wire Schema enforcement</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>5. Ownership proof check</td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-stub">Non-empty check only</span></td>
        <td><span class="badge badge-ok">Chain-specific signature verify</span></td>
        <td>Add ChainVerificationContext parameter to Right::verify()</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
